descript.abstract: Important Bird Areas (IBA) of California as described by Cooper (2004) and represented by points identifying the center of sites, areas, and other polygonal features. Each point supports information about sensitive (special concern, threatened, endangered, otherwise declining or vulnerable) bird species occurrence. The DFG verified digitized locations with Audubon GIS contractors, corrected some location and position errors, and added attributes for each species addressed in the IBA publication.
descript.purpose: These data are intended as general occurrence support information for conservation planning and, when used in conjunction with other occurrence data, for describing range. They are not intended, and should not be used, as support for regulatory programs or as documentation of current species occurrence at a location.

attracc.attraccr: Two species (Redhead, Yellow-headed Blackbird) not listed in Table 1 (pp12-16), but included in various IBA sensitive species lists were added to the attribute table. Two IBAs (Ballona Valley, Sierra Meadows - Southern) found in the text, but not in the original shapefile, were added and approved by the author. Perceived inconsistencies/errors found during this project are delineated in the Word document IBA_discrepancies.doc., which was provided to the author. The specified coordinates in the Lat./Long. fields correspond to the original projection and not this shapefile's coordinate system.

IBA name as published in Cooper (2004).

Number of taxa that exceed the population threshold of 1% of global or 10% of state population (P). Additional 1 point if the IBA is reported to support >9 "sensitive" taxa (L), > 10,000 shorebirds (S), and >5,000 waterfowl (W). Example - The Orange Coast Wetlands IBA reportedly supports 3 taxa with >1% of their global population occurring at the IBA (3 points), 3 taxa with >10% of their state population occurring at the IBA (3 points), greater than 9 sensitive taxa (1 point), greater than 10,000 shorebirds (1 point), and greater than 5,000 waterfowl (1 point) for a total of 9 points.
Total number of sensitive species reported from the IBA.

Critical: Most of habitat at immediate risk of alteration by human activity. High: Most of habitat at some level of risk, or substantial amount of habitat at immediate risk. Medium: Substantial amount of habitat at some level of risk, or small amount at immediate risk. Low: Small amount of habitat at some level of risk, or area well protected and well managed.
Partners in Flight Bird Conservation Regions. BCR 5 - Northern Pacific Rainforest; BCR 9 - Great Basin; BCR 15 - Sierra Nevada; BCR 23 - Coastal California; BCR 33 - Sonoran and Mojave Desert.
A 3-tiered rank that was assigned based on the score field, with 9 being a score of 20 or higher, 6 being middle (undefined), 3 being lowest (undefined).
USDA Forest Service ecological subsections (Miles and Goudey 1997)

Santa Cruz Island Rufus Crowned Sparrow
